BIMAS-2 SURVEY HAS BEEN EXTENDED TO SEPTEMBER 11.

ATTENTION STARPOINT FAMILIES: Please check your email accounts for a message from Edumetrisis, author of the BIMAS-2.
This is a social/emotional survey we are hoping all parents can complete before September 11, and will help us identify students in need of immediate assistance with social and emotional needs upon returning to instruction. You should have a link for each of your children. Please call Carrie Mansour, School Psychologist at 210-2328 with questions you may have.

post_text:
Attention all Parents:

Currently Transportation Change Forms for the 2020-21 school year are due on July 31st as the District does not have any guidance from NYS regarding re-opening . It is anticipated that once guidance comes out from NYS and the District has had a chance to review and make decisions regarding re-opening, forms and deadlines may change.

Thank you for your patience through all of this. Please know that District Staff and Administration are working diligently so that when the guidance from NYS comes out, the District will be in a position to act quickly and give parents and guardians ample time to make decisions regarding their children.

post_text:
A must watch video from Starpoint 8th grader Chorus students!!

It's a beautiful day to celebrate our 8th graders!
It brought me joy delivering gifts and diploma's to them today. At the same time, it was sad to see their last year at the Middle School end without our traditional Graduation and Awards Assembly. Usually, the 8th Grade Chorus sings a final inspirational selection as a "send off" at the end of the ceremony.
Now that the diplomas and awards are delivered, I'm very proud to share this video.
It celebrates the power of music to lift our spirits. The lyrics remind us that when we are facing challenges, we can always reach out to others for support.
Wishing everyone a healthy and relaxing summer!

ðŸŽ¼Julie Arlotta

Showcasing another amazing Senior!
Anya Fink is a senior who decided to make her own prom dress during Mrs. Tomasello's Fashion Design class. "In early March she showed me her elaborate sketches and day by day she added to her fashion mannequin. When we got the word that schools needed to close, it didnâ€™t stop her. She continued to work from home to make this vision a reality. Never did she think that prom would be cancelled and that she would not be able to wear her beautiful homemade dress. I asked her if we can share it on Facebook because I think she deserves some extra attention for completely designing this dress from scratch! Iâ€™m very proud of her!"

H.S. Art Teacher - Mrs. Tomasello

UPDATED Absentee Ballot Information - June 4, 2020

We have been notified by the various Post Offices that:
Absentee Ballots for the 14094 zip code were delivered into homes on June 2nd and Absentee Ballots for the 14120 and 14132 zip codes have been delivered into homes on June 3rd.

If you don't receive a ballot by Wednesday, June 3rd, please contact the District Clerk, Dorothy Szpaicher at dszpaicher@starpointcsd.org or by calling 716-210-2352. She will need the full name, full address including township and zip code and dates of birth for all eligible voters in your home.

Also, absentee ballot drop boxes will be located at the HS and MS main entrances Wednesday, June 3rd - Friday, June 5th (8am-4pm) as well as Monday, June 8th (8am-4pm) and Tuesday, June 9th (8am-5pm).

Thank you.

May the 4th be with you!

Monday morning, Mrs. Fuqua's Kindergarten class celebrated May 4th with a special class meeting on Zoom. They wore their favorite Star Wars gear that included a stormtrooper mask, a Darth Vader mask; and one family had a large cutout of Chewie that attended our meeting! Mrs. Fuqua was even dressed as Rey! My students and their families had fun learning how to draw Baby Yoda. They did an amazing job! May the force be strong with everyone during this time!

#OneStarpoint Families,

Governor Cuomo has extended 'NYS on Pause'; therefore Starpoint CSD will remain closed to students through May 15th.

We will continue to provide our food service (breakfast/lunch) on campus on Mondays, Wednesdays, and Fridays as well as our continuity of learning/remote instruction to students. Please stay tuned for additional information in the days and weeks to come.

Thank you and stay safe,

Dr. Croft
Superintendent of Schools

WiFi Connectivity Issues with Chromebooks

Anyone with a Starpoint Chromebook that is not connecting to their home WiFi will need to restart the computer. There was a device setting that needed to be adjusted. Once you restart the computer your home WiFi network will appear, you will be able to connect to it, and your child will be able to login to their account. Sorry for the inconvenience and thank you for your patience.

text:
For the 3rd year in a row, the Fricano 2nd grade classes are collecting donations for the local animal rescue group Diamonds in the Ruff.

At the end of March, volunteers from DITR will be coming to collect the donations, speak to our students about responsible pet ownership, and show photos of some of the animals that are up for donation. Our students love this presentation!

If you would like to help make this the biggest collection year yet, please consider making a personal donation. The items that are the most helpful for the animals are:
-dry cat food and dry dog food;
-can cat food and can dog food;
-kitty litter;
-treats for dogs and cats;
-collars and leashes;
-toys;
-gift cards or cash donations.
Items can be dropped off in the Fricano Main Office until the end of March.
If you would like to learn more about Diamonds in the Ruff, please visit their website:
https://diamondsintheruffanimalrescue.rescuegroups.org/

Julie Arlottaâ€™s 8th Grade Chorus students spread some joy through music in the lobby of Roswell Park Comprehensive Cancer Center on Tuesday, December 10, 2019. Students shared uplifting holiday tunes for all to listen as they filled the lobby with song and their youthful spirit. They even witnessed some exciting victory bells while they were there and cheered to help celebrate their accomplishments! The victory bell rings whenever a patient receives good news, finishes a treatment or experiences a personal victory.

The whole Middle School supported this event! Students and staff donated fuzzy socks. Mrs. Wynes and her FACS students made ornaments. A studentâ€™s grandmother made pillows. These wonderful gifts, along with handmade cards by all of our students were delivered for patients. It was a very special day giving back to our community during the holiday season!

Last seen on stage as The Cat in the Hat in Starpoint Middle School's production of Seussical Jr., Ryan Butler has moved on to professional theater!
We are so proud of Ryan and wish him well in Pete the Cat at Buffalo's Theater of Youth.

RYAN BUTLER (Jimmy) Ryan is thrilled to be in his first professional theatre performance here at TOY! He is currently a freshman at Starpoint High School. Ryan's past performances include: Seussical (Cat in the Hat), Xanadu (Sonny Malone), and Camp Rock. He has attended several dance classes, including musical theatre, and has enjoyed performing in many talent shows. Ryan is grateful for this opportunity, and hopes to continue in theatre for years to come. Special thanks to his family, and Bobby, for everything.
http://www.theatreofyouth.org/event/10cca4e6c3170c9f631ce23002e64aff

post_text:
Thank you to Rich Tomasello, local artist and educator, for including over 100 Starpoint High School students in his installation â€œSafe Spaceâ€ for the art show titled Play/Ground last weekend. Students plastered school related objects to be included with his own plaster based work. The room is meant to convey the fears and anxieties faced by many American school children where lock down drills are commonplace and students and teachers alike must choose between run, hide, or fight. Although seemingly dark in context, his work features
paper airplanes emerging from the pile of desks to symbolize a feeling
of hope.

post_text: The modified soccer teams are once again collecting items for the Ronald McDonald House of Buffalo. The Ronald McDonald House provides a safe, comfortable place for families to stay while their child is in a local hospital. They offer rooms as well as meals, mostly free of charge, for over 500 families each year. Please consider donating to this worthy cause. The House needs snack size chips, cookies, and fruit snacks, granola bars, bottles of water, and many household items. The entire Wish List is posted throughout the school (and can be found here https://rmhcwny.org/helping-at-the-house/m-wish-list/) and there are collection boxes in the Main Lobby as well as at the Attendance Office. Thank you for your support.

Starpoint is Accepting Applications for their
Academic Wall of Fame & Sports Wall of Fame

The Starpoint Central School District is accepting nominations for both the Academic Wall of Fame and Sports Wall of Fame for the 2019-20 school year. Nominees for both Alumni Walls of Fame should be graduates between the years of 1958-2004. Nomination information and applications can be downloaded from the school's website at www.starpointcsd.org under the Parents/Community tab, click on Alumni, click on Alumni Wall of Fame Nominations, or by contacting Jane Wilson jwilson@starpointcsd.org or by telephone at 210-2307 for more information.

Nominations will be accepted until October 1, 2019 for the Academic Wall of Fame and Achievement and until November 1, 2019 for the Sports Wall of Fame.

We appreciate your support and hope to see in March!

Starpoint High School Art students worked with local artist, Edreys Wajed, earlier this month as they learned about Buffaloâ€™s Freedom Wall, a large mural of 28 portraits of civil rights leaders. Edreys was one of the 4 artists on this project. He taught the students about perseverance, that hard work leads to opportunities, and how his own art evolved. After demonstrating his line technique, students had the opportunity to try it themselves before embarking on their own portraits. Thank you for an inspiring visit, Edreys!
(Art pictured below is by Edreys Wajed)

post_text:
Starpoint High School Diversity Club and VYO (voice your opinion) Club members came together to volunteer at the WNY Food Bank on Thursday April 11th.
The Food Bank distributes approximately 3,600 weekend meals that are sent home each Friday to students in need.

Our students packed 6,054 pounds of food for that program. The Food Bank has creatively adopted a Eco-friendly program that turns unused t-shirts into reusable tote bags. These bags are loaded with fruits and vegetables when food is distributed to low income families. Our students also donated their time to create over 50 bags that will be used for this purpose. The students truly enjoyed participating and left feeling proud of the contribution they made.

A BIG thank you to the following students who gave of their time: Dexter Brooks, Iris Garcia, Allyson Harry, Karie Hawkins, Jenna Lang, Sydney Licata, Casey Miller, Samantha Nicosia, Katie O'Connor, Riddhi Patel, Karri Perry, Emily Roneker, Emily Strobel, Thia Thothongkum and Shayla Tillman

The Alumni Class of 2015's 6th Annual Art, Music, and Food Truck Festival (& Classic Car Show) will be held on Friday, May 31 (5:00 pm-8:30 pm). This event has been VERY successful and it continues to grow every year. This year 7 food trucks will be attending- Lloyd, Cheesy Chick, B&L BBQ, Seas the Day, The Sweet Hearth, Ru's Pierogi, and Pizza Amore. Student artists and musicians from the entire district will be represented throughout the evening.

Last year we added several large inflatables for kids to enjoy and a DUNK TANK, which were huge hits!

With the money raised through this event the Alumni Class of 2015 gives back to Starpoint School District and their community through their "Starpoint Cares" Fund. This school year alone they gifted $2250 back into the Starpoint community; the Dale Askey Courtyard Fall maintenance (nearly $1100), gift cards to a Starpoint family who lost their home to a tragic fire ($750) supporting the Starpoint HS musical through it's advertising campaign ($200).
cash prizes for the school talent competition ($200)

Hope to see many of you there!

post_text:
Starpoint Switches to Paper Straws!

The hard work and efforts of Miss Smithâ€™s 7th and 8th grade ELA Lab students really paid off! They have been researching and brainstorming solutions to combat the dangers of plastic pollution and the negative effects plastic has on our ecosystem. They applied this knowledge to their everyday experiences here at Starpoint MS by writing letters and meeting with Dr. Croft to discuss the amount of plastic pollution we generate here at the school.

Dr. Croft supported their suggestions and has agreed to switch from plastic straws to paper straws throughout the district! Congratulations to Ms. Smithâ€™s 7th and 8th grade classes for making such a positive change here at Starpoint! Look for paper straws, as they will be in all our Starpoint cafeterias soon!

WGRZ - Channel 2, Buffalo
News 4 WIVB Buffalo
7 Eyewitness News WKBW

post_text:
Congratulations to 10th Grader, Natalie O'Brien, who will be recognized at this Saturday's Sabres game as the LECOM All-Star student.

Mr. Dunlop found out last night that after recommending Natalie O'Brien she will be recognized on the ice, this Saturday at the Sabres game, as the LECOM All-Star student, for not only being an honors student in the HS, but also for her pioneering effort which successfully landed Starpoint, NW, NT, and Lew-Port a Federation girls high school hockey team. At the end there is a link to an article briefly explaining the recognition.

As a part of the recognition, she gets a customized jersey, a blurb read about her prior to the Sabres starting lineup, and four tickets to the game. She is only one of 5 students to be recognized this season, so it's a pretty big deal.

If you see her or her mom in the MS, Diane, please congratulate them on this honor.

https://www.wnypapers.com/news/article/current/2018/10/16/134507/lecom-unveils-student-all-stars-program-at-sabres-games

post_text:
With less than 48 hours notice, #OneStarpoint pulled together and prepared Starpoint High School to host the 2019 Section VI Championships on Sunday, February 3rd!

Mrs. Jena Zubricky, Mr. Dave Ciurczak and Mr. Tom Sarkovics were instrumental in leading our team to prepare for this premier event which brought 40 different schools to Starpoint to compete on Sunday.

Beyond these 3 amazing leaders, we couldn't have done it without these members of our #OneStarpoint team: Sean Healy, Jane Wilson, Sam Doak, Set up-> Valerie Rechtsiegel and Derek Cutter, Event-> Samantha Sylvester and Paul Jacus, Clean up-> Julie Schul-Bliven, Dan Proefrock, Frank Dispenza, and Janine Walters. We are grateful to have such an amazing staff!

All our hard work paid off when Starpoint Varsity Cheerleading were crowned the 2019 Section VI Champions!
